    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "my realtor just mentioned i need to deal with an escrow account for the house closing in toronto. i've never heard of that before. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's used during the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral holding zone, much like a safe kept by a trusted third party, where funds and documents are stored until the closing conditions are met. In the context of a Toronto real estate transaction, this is crucial because it ensures that the buyer's money isn't transferred to the seller until the property is legally clear, and the seller's funds aren't released until the buyer has secured their title. It acts as a buffer against any last-minute surprises, like a hidden leak or a missing permit, which could otherwise derail the deal.\n\nThink of it as a game of musical chairs where the chairs are the legal requirements; if the music stops (the conditions aren't met), the money stays in the middle, and no one gets the house. This system protects both parties from each other, ensuring that the transaction is fair and secure. Without escrow, you'd be dealing directly with the other party, which is far more risky and chaotic.\n\nIn Toronto specifically, the complexity of the market means that escrow agents are often busy managing multiple transactions simultaneously, so it's vital to communicate clearly with them. They act as the conductors of the orchestra, making sure every instrument (document, wire, inspection) plays",
      "source": "target",
