    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically it's just a way to make sure nobody gets cheated. but who actually holds the money? like is it the realtor, or a bank, or someone else? and how do they make sure the money stays safe until everything is officially done?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The money is typically held by a specialized third-party entity, often a title company, a lawyer (which is very common in Ontario/Toronto), or sometimes a bank, but rarely the realtor themselves. The realtor is just the guide; they don't hold the purse strings.\n\nTo ensure the money stays safe, these institutions use strict, computerized protocols that require specific triggers to release funds. It's like a vault that only opens when a specific combination of keys is turned simultaneously. For example, the bank might not release the buyer's funds until the lawyer confirms the title search is clean, and the lawyer won't sign off until the buyer's funds are verified. If one link in the chain is missing, the money just sits there, safe and sound, until the puzzle is complete.\n\nIt's a bit like a group of very strict, very busy goblins guarding a treasure chest in the middle of a busy street. If even one goblin says, \"Hey, I found a crack in the floor!\" or \"Wait, the door handle is rusted,\" the treasure stays locked up. The goblins are the ones doing the checking, and they are notoriously good at finding problems before anyone else notices. In fact",
